## Mason County has the highest share of kids going to non-parent sponsors in Washington. Adams County is second, and all other counties have much lower rates.

### Visualization 3: Chloropleth map of WA counties 

### Load WA population data

```{r}

# using census data to get county population data
wa_county_map <- get_acs(
  geography = "county", 
  state = "wa", 
  variables = "B01003_001", 
  geometry = T
)
```

### Getting + joining zipcode data

```{r}

# Getting zipcode data for WA
zip_to_county_WA <- zipcodeR::zip_code_db %>%
  filter(state == "WA") %>%
  transmute(
    sponsor_zipcode = zipcode,
    county   = county,    
  )

# Joining data and narrowing it down
wa_nonparent <- nyt_mc %>%
  left_join(zip_to_county_WA, by = "sponsor_zipcode") %>%
  filter(
    !is.na(county),              
    sponsor_category %in% c("2","3")
  )

```

### Assigning zipcodes to counties

```{r}
# Build WA county FIPS from names
norm_county <- function(x) {
  x |>
    stringr::str_to_lower() |>
    stringr::str_replace_all("\\bcounty\\b", "") |>
    stringr::str_replace_all("[^a-z ]", " ") |>
    stringr::str_squish()
}

wa_fips <- tidycensus::fips_codes %>%
  filter(state == "WA") %>%
  transmute(
    county_name_clean = norm_county(county),               # "mason"
    county_fips       = paste0(state_code, county_code)    # e.g., "53045"
  ) %>%
  distinct()

wa_counts <- wa_nonparent %>%
  mutate(county_name_clean = norm_county(county)) %>%
  inner_join(wa_fips, by = "county_name_clean") %>%
  count(county_fips, name = "children_nonparent")

```

### Joining counts with shapes/population + finding rate

```{r}
wa_rates <- wa_county_map %>%
  mutate(GEOID = as.character(GEOID)) %>%
  transmute(
    county_fips = stringr::str_pad(GEOID, width = 5, pad = "0"),
    county_name = NAME,
    population  = estimate,
    geometry
  ) %>%
  left_join(wa_counts, by = "county_fips") %>%
  mutate(
    children_nonparent = tidyr::replace_na(children_nonparent, 0L),
    rate_per_100k      = 100000 * children_nonparent / population
  )
```

### Creating visualization

```{r}

brks <- round(pretty(range(wa_rates$rate_per_100k, na.rm = TRUE), n = 5))

p_rate <- ggplot(wa_rates, aes(fill = rate_per_100k)) +
  geom_sf(color = "black", linewidth = 0.25) +
 scale_fill_gradientn(
  colors = RColorBrewer::brewer.pal(9, "Blues"),
  breaks = brks,  # ← integer ticks
  labels = function(x) formatC(x, format = "f", digits = 0, big.mark = ","),  # ← no decimals
  na.value = "grey90",
  name = "Kids per 100,000 residents"
) +
  labs(
    title    = "Mason County has the highest rate of kids going to non-parents",
    caption  = "U.S. HHS via NYT release; population via Census; analysis by Jessica Baugh
    *One child had no sponsor category",
    x = NULL, y = NULL
  ) +
  theme_void(base_size = 12) +
  theme(legend.position = "right")

p_rate
```

# Limitations 

The HHS data that I have tracks the initial county where each child is released, but it does not show whether the child remains there for long. Therefore, if these children are not enrolling in school in this county, this could impact the number of programs that are being created or managed to address this population.

# Methods 

This analysis uses federal data from the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, which was made public by The New York Times. The dataset spans from January 2015 to May 2023. Each row represents an unaccompanied child released to a sponsor, with fields for the sponsor's zip code and category. I filtered the data for zip codes in Mason County and then used it to produce counts for sponsor type and totals over time.
To align sponsors' zipcodes with counties, I used the zipcodeR package to map each zipcode to its county FIPS, then joined the migrant child data to the appropriate counties throughout Washington. I merged these results with the 2023 American Community Survey county population estimates to create the choropleth map, which shows rates of children going to non-parent sponsors by 100,000.
I produced the visuals in my R Markdown file, titled 570-final-pitch-baugh.Rmd. These include:
- Sponsor category bar chart: Determined using Mason County releases by sponsor category data. 
- Change over time line chart: Quarterly totals for Mason County, with the share going to non-parent sponsor highlighted. 
- Choropleth map: Joined county totals to the Washington shape file to visualize the share of non-parent placements across the state by county. 
